@F. Gaynor
Nice job noticing the trend in the data!  When you say "there is a fluctuation in how conservative versus liberal justices have been," what do you mean by that?
I also like that you are thinking about how this graph could be used.  Data often tells an interesting story - but it can also be used to persuade.

@N. Ford
Interesting prediction about how the score might change as the older justices begin to retire.  What impacts the type of judge that is nominated when a seat opens up?
An interesting inference as well about the relationship between decisions made in society versus those made in the courts.  Do you think one has more impact on the other?

@Ryan
Thank you for noticing, wondering, AND giving a headline.  

Your headline is "Political Nominees' Change in Ideological Views".  Would you give us evidence from the graph as to which ones have changed the most?  The least?  What conclusions can you come up with from these observations?

@Kyle B
You bring up so many good noticings and wonderings, plus a headline, too.
You wonder if, since Justice Kennedy is “closest to the Martin-Quinn score, does this mean that he has the least amount of political perspective on cases.”  Ask your classmates.  What is the Martin-Quinn score on the graph?  And, what is the median justice?  What does it mean when Justice Kennedy is close to each of these lines?  These incidences can say a lot about the Court.

@Carson
Very, very interesting that you observed that justices nominated by Democratic versus Republican presidents vary in how their ideology starts as well as how it changes over time.  What does this imply?
You say that the Court is polarized.  What do you see in the graph that supports this claim?

@Jane
Thank you for kicking off today’s Supreme Court graph.  On Monday, the 2018 - 2019 session opened with the announcement of cases they will take on.
You notice that there is a line for median justice.  I wonder how this compares to the Martin-Quinn score of zero.  (You may want to search for what is the Martin-Quinn score, how it is calculated, and what it means.)  Regarding your questioning the start of Justice Ginsburg’s confirmation, viewers should always examine and confirm the inputs to a graph.  Do a quick search to see if the graph is in error.
